- Focused Best Of Men At Work: jangly layered guitars and tight multi‑tracked harmonies align exactly with my preference for jangly midrange guitars and two‑part harmonies. The description calls out a tactile midrange and warm sheen plus a restrained remaster that preserves headroom and transients — that matches my low‑compression, preserved micro‑dynamics preference. “Spare punchy mixes” and “wide stereo imaging” imply clear instrument separation, snappy transients and restrained production rather than glossy, over‑produced mastering. The presence of tasteful sax and propulsive synth‑bass is presented as tasteful and supportive rather than synth/club‑forward, so it does not conflict necessarily with my dislike of synth‑forward hooks. Full‑length sequencing and a restrained remaster suggest performances that breathe rather than being sequenced to death. Lead vocal character for Men At Work (multi‑tracked harmonies, front focal mixes) is consistent with my taste for front‑and‑center, weathered lead vocals with audible presence.
- Bright, guitar‑forward AOR: this CD ticks many technical boxes I like — guitar‑forward, low‑compression mastering, snappy transients, punchy mids, generous headroom and dry center‑front vocals — and the intimate, revealing mixes are attractive. But it is explicitly described as “bright” with “immediate top‑end presence.” That bright, forward top end maps directly to my stated dislike of bright upper‑mid harshness and immediate top‑end glare. The emphasis on dry, center‑front vocals and immediate top end risks sacrificing the warm analogue sheen and tactile midrange I prioritize. While it’s vocal‑forward and hook‑focused (which I like to an extent), the AOR brightness and immediate top‑end presence make it more likely to feel glossy or fatiguing rather than the restrained, warm, live‑in‑studio sound I prefer.
3) Why I choose Focused Best Of Men At Work and reject the AOR disc:
- The Men At Work collection better matches my top priorities: midrange‑forward, jangly guitar textures; tight supporting harmonies; a warm analogue sheen; and a restrained remaster that preserves headroom and transients. Those are explicit positives in the Men At Work description and map closely to my stated preferences for tactile midrange, preserved micro‑dynamics, and front‑and‑center but not over‑processed vocals. The “spare punchy mixes” and preservation of full‑length sequencing strongly suggest the natural band interplay and breathing performances I value.
- In contrast, the AOR release, while technically competent (low compression, snappy transients, punchy mids), is explicitly characterized by brightness and “immediate top‑end presence.” That conflicts with my explicit dislike of bright upper‑mid harshness and any production that trades warm analogue character for top‑end sheen. Even though the AOR’s dry, center‑front vocals and intimate mixes could be appealing, the tonal emphasis on brightness and immediate top end makes it a less faithful fit for my preference for warm, midrange‑centred, analogue‑sheened recordings with restrained production and preserved dynamics.
- Finally, Men At Work’s combination of jangly midrange guitars, tasteful vintage elements (sax), multi‑tracked harmonies and a restrained remaster reads as the better match for the “tactile midrange and warm sheen” I described, whereas the AOR’s brightness risks crossing into the kind of upper‑mid harshness and glossy character I explicitly dislike.
For all these reasons I select Focused Best Of Men At Work and reject the bright AOR option.

